      "source": [
        "# Rearsch Area Map\n",
        "\n",
        "This notebook builds a **two-panel figure** in one run:\n",
        "\n",
        "- **Panel A (left):** Greyscale terrain from `earth_relief` (30 arc-second), hillshade, coastlines, and geographic annotations. A black dashed rectangle marks the extent reused for panel B.\n",
        "- **Panel B (right):** Esri World Imagery obtained via **contextily** as Web Mercator GeoTIFFs, then **`gdalwarp`**’d to **WGS84** on exactly `FOX_REGION`. PyGMT **`grdimage`** plots that raster under the same Mercator projection as the map frame (GMT **`image`** would not—see code comments below).\n",
        "\n",
        "Grey connector lines link the dashed box corners on panel A to the matching corners on panel B using **`gmt mapproject`** so coordinates stay consistent with GMT’s map geometry.\n",
        "\n",
        "---\n",
        "\n",
        "### Requirements\n",
        "\n",
        "- **Python:** 3.x with `pygmt`, `numpy`, `contextily`.\n",
        "- **CLI:** `gmt` and `gdalwarp` discoverable on `PATH` (conda-forge stacks usually install both under the env `bin/`).\n",
        "- **Working directory:** Keep this notebook at the **repository root**; the first code cell sets `ROOT` to **`ResearchArea/`** (created if missing) so GeoTIFFs and `south_island_dem.png` stay in that folder.\n",
        "\n",
        "### Outputs\n",
        "\n",
        "| File | Role |\n",
        "|------|------|\n",
        "| `south_island_dem.png` | Final figure (300 dpi in last cell). |\n",
        "| `south_island_relief.cpt` | Land-only grey CPT from DEM range. |\n",
        "| `south_island_intensity.nc` | Hillshade grid for `grdimage`. |\n",
        "| `fox_basemap_raw.tif` | Tiles in EPSG:3857 from contextily. |\n",
        "| `fox_basemap_plot.tif` | Warped to WGS84 for PyGMT `grdimage`. |\n",
        "\n",
        "### Cell order\n",
        "\n",
        "Run **cells 1 → 2 → 3** once per full rebuild. Cell 1 fixes Jupyter/conda `PATH` issues and defines constants; cell 2 defines helpers; cell 3 loads data, computes layout, draws, saves, and shows in IPython.\n",
        "\n"
      ]
    },
    {
